**Time of maximal specific activity**  

When the labeling kinetics are faster than radioactive decay (\(\lambda\ll k_{p},k_{\text{assoc}}^{\max}\theta_{\infty}\)) the peak occurs when the instantaneous labeling rate equals the sum of dissociation and decay rates.  This yields the closed‑form

\[
\boxed{%
t_{\max}= \frac{1}{k_{p}}\;
\ln\!\left[
\frac{k_{\text{assoc}}^{\max}\,\theta_{\infty}}
{k_{\text{diss}}^{0}+\lambda}
\right]
=
\frac{1}{k_{\text{on}}[H^{+}]+k_{\text{off}}}\;
\ln\!\left[
\frac{k_{\text{assoc}}^{\max}\,
\displaystyle\frac{k_{\text{on}}[H^{+}]}
{k_{\text{on}}[H^{+}]+k_{\text{off}}}}
{k_{\text{diss}}^{0}+\frac{\ln 2}{T_{1/2}}}
\right] } .
\]

If the diffusion coefficient modulation is retained (\(D_{\text{eff}}=D_{0}[1+\alpha\theta(t)]\)), the association term in the logarithm is multiplied by \((1+\alpha\theta_{\infty})\); i.e.  

\[
k_{\text{assoc}}^{\max}\;\rightarrow\;k_{\text{assoc}}^{\max}\bigl(1+\alpha\theta_{\infty}\bigr)
\]

in the expression for \(t_{\max}\).  

These formulas give the full time‑dependent specific activity and the time at which it reaches its maximum, expressed solely in terms of the kinetic parameters, neutron‑production rate, decay constant, and initial chelator concentration.

**Answer**

\[
\boxed{\;
\mathcal E_{n}=K_{1}(\alpha,\gamma)\,\sigma^{\alpha}\,n^{-(2\gamma-1)}
\Bigl[1+\tilde c\,n^{-\lambda}+o(n^{-\lambda})\Bigr]
\;+\;
