\;}
\tag{1}
\]

where  

* \(K_{1}(\alpha,\gamma)=\dfrac{C_{\alpha,\gamma}}{(2\gamma-1)\pi}\) with  
\(C_{\alpha,\gamma}= \sigma^{\alpha}\bigl|1-\sum_{k\ge1}\theta_k e^{-ik\omega}\bigr|^{-\alpha}\big|_{\omega\to0}\) (the constant that multiplies the low‑frequency singularity \(f(\omega)\sim C_{\alpha,\gamma}|\omega|^{2\gamma-2}\)).  

* \(\tilde c=\dfrac{K_{2}}{K_{1}}\) comes from the first regular term in the spectral expansion  
\(f(\omega)=C_{\alpha,\gamma}|\omega|^{2\gamma-2}\bigl[1+c_{1}|\omega|^{\lambda}+o(|\omega|^{\lambda})\bigr]\) (\(\lambda>0\)).  

* \(K_{3}(\alpha,\beta,\gamma)=\dfrac{1}{(\alpha\gamma-1)^{\beta/\alpha}}
\,\frac{\Gamma(1-\beta/\alpha)}{\Gamma(1-\beta)}\) (a positive constant that links the scale of an \(\alpha\)-stable law to its finite \(\beta\)-moment).  

The two algebraic rates are  

\[
\boxed{\;\delta = 2\gamma-1,\qquad 
\eta   = \beta\Bigl(\gamma-\frac1\alpha\Bigr)\;}
\tag{2}
\]

and the dominant term in (1) is the one that decays **more slowly**.  

Define the **critical decay exponent**

\[
\boxed{\;
\gamma_{c}(\alpha,\beta)=\frac{1+\beta/\alpha}{\,2-\beta\,}\;}
\tag{3}
\]

which solves \(\delta=\eta\).  

* If \(\displaystyle \gamma<\gamma_{c}(\alpha,\beta)\) then \(\delta<\eta\) and the long‑memory (spectral) part dominates:
\[
\mathcal E_{n}=K_{1}(\alpha,\gamma)\,\sigma^{\alpha}\,n^{-\delta}
\Bigl[1+\tilde c\,n^{-\lambda}+o(n^{-\lambda})\Bigr].
\]

* If \(\displaystyle \gamma>\gamma_{c}(\alpha,\beta)\) then \(\eta<\delta\) and the heavy‑tail contribution dominates:
\[
\mathcal E_{n}=K_{3}(\alpha,\beta,\gamma)\,\sigma^{\beta}\,n^{-\eta}\;(1+o(1)).
\]

Thus the optimal finite‑dimensional linear prediction error decays as a power law \(n^{-\delta}\) when the autoregressive coefficients are sufficiently persistent (\(\gamma<\gamma_{c}\)), and switches to a different power law \(n^{-\eta}\) when the coefficients decay faster (\(\gamma>\gamma_{c}\)). The exponents \(\delta\) and \(\eta\) depend explicitly on the stability index \(\alpha\), the finite‑\(\beta\) moment exponent \(\beta\), and the tail exponent \(\gamma\) of the AR coefficients, while the scale parameter \(\sigma\) enters through the prefactors \(K_{1}\) and \(K_{3}\).

**Steady‑state concentration of \(^{233}\mathrm{U}\)**  

\[
\boxed{
[^{233}\mathrm{U}]_{\mathrm{ss}}=
\frac{
\displaystyle 
\frac{b_{Np\!\to\!U}^{c}\,\sigma_{c}(^{237}\! \mathrm{Np})\,\phi}
      {\lambda_{U}+\sigma_{c}(^{233}\! \mathrm{U})\phi+\sigma_{f}(^{233}\! \mathrm{U})\phi}
\;
\frac{b_{Pu\!\to\!Np}^{c}\,\sigma_{c}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu})\,\phi}
      {\lambda_{Np}+\sigma_{c}(^{237}\! \mathrm{Np})\phi+\sigma_{f}(^{237}\! \mathrm{Np})\phi}
\;
\frac{b_{Am\!\to\!Pu}\,\lambda_{Am}+b_{Am\!\to\!Pu}^{c}\,\sigma_{c}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Am})\phi}
      {\lambda_{Pu}+\sigma_{c}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu})\phi+\sigma_{f}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu})\phi}
}
{
\displaystyle 
\underbrace{\bigl[\nu_{Pu}(1-\beta_{Pu})\sigma_{f}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu})\phi\,\alpha_{Pu}
          +\nu_{U}(1-\beta_{U})\sigma_{f}(^{233}\! \mathrm{U})\phi\,\alpha_{U}\bigr]}_{\alpha_{\text{source}}}
-
\underbrace{\bigl[\sigma_{c}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Am})\phi
          +\sigma_{c}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu})\phi\,\alpha_{Pu}
          +\sigma_{c}(^{237}\! \mathrm{Np})\phi\,\alpha_{Np}
          +\sigma_{c}(^{233}\! \mathrm{U})\phi\,\alpha_{U}\bigr]}_{\alpha_{\text{capture}}}
}\;
\Gamma_{\text{loss}}
}
\]

where  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\alpha_{Pu}&=
\frac{b_{Am\!\to\!Pu}\,\lambda_{Am}+b_{Am\!\to\!Pu}^{c}\,\sigma_{c}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Am})\phi}
      {\lambda_{Pu}+\sigma_{c}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu})\phi+\sigma_{f}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu})\phi},\\[4pt]
\alpha_{Np}&=
\frac{b_{Pu\!\to\!Np}^{c}\,\sigma_{c}(^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu})\phi}
      {\lambda_{Np}+\sigma_{c}(^{237}\! \mathrm{Np})\phi+\sigma_{f}(^{237}\! \mathrm{Np})\phi},\\[4pt]
\alpha_{U}&=
\frac{b_{Np\!\to\!U}^{c}\,\sigma_{c}(^{237}\! \mathrm{Np})\phi}
      {\lambda_{U}+\sigma_{c}(^{233}\! \mathrm{U})\phi+\sigma_{f}(^{233}\! \mathrm{U})\phi}.
\end{aligned}
\]

All symbols have their usual meaning:

* \([X]\) – number density (atoms cm\(^{-3}\)) of nuclide \(X\);  
* \(\sigma_{c}(X),\ \sigma_{f}(X)\) – effective (self‑shielded) capture and fission microscopic cross‑sections (cm\(^2\));  
* \(\phi\) – spatially‑averaged neutron flux (cm\(^{-2}\) s\(^{-1}\));  
* \(\lambda_{X}=\ln 2/t_{1/2,X}\) – decay constant of \(X\);  
* \(b_{i\!\to\!j}^{c}\) – branching ratio for the neutron‑capture (or decay) reaction that converts \(i\) into \(j\) (unity for the dominant pathways);  
* \(\nu_{i}\) – average number of neutrons per fission of \(i\);  
* \(\beta_{i}\) – total delayed‑neutron fraction for fission of \(i\);  
* \(\Gamma_{\text{loss}}\) – net loss term (leakage + parasitic capture) required to close the global neutron‑balance equation  

\[
\sum_i \nu_i(1-\beta_i)\sigma_f(i)\phi[i]
=
\sum_j \sigma_c(j)\phi[j] + \Gamma_{\text{loss}} .
\]

---

### Conditions for a non‑trivial, physically stable equilibrium  

1. **Criticality (or near‑criticality)**  
   \[
   \alpha_{\text{source}}=\alpha_{\text{capture}}
   \quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad k_{\mathrm{eff}}\approx 1 .
   \]
   When \(\Gamma_{\text{loss}}=0\) this equality must hold; a small positive \(\Gamma_{\text{loss}}\) permits operation with \(k_{\mathrm{eff}}<1\).

2. **Positive total loss rates**  
   \[
   \lambda_{X}+\sigma_{c}(X)\phi+\sigma_{f}(X)\phi>0
   \qquad\forall X\in\{^{241}\! \mathrm{Am},^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu},^{237}\! \mathrm{Np},^{233}\! \mathrm{U}\},
   \]
   which is always satisfied for real nuclear data, guaranteeing that all eigenvalues of the kinetic matrix have negative real parts and that perturbations decay exponentially.

3. **Dominant forward branching**  
   The product of the three capture‑to‑loss ratios in the numerator must be non‑zero; i.e. the capture pathways \(^{241}\! \mathrm{Am}\!\to\!^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu}\), \(^{241}\! \mathrm{Pu}\!\to\!^{237}\! \mathrm{Np}\) and \(^{237}\! \mathrm{Np}\!\to\!^{233}\! \mathrm{U}\) must have appreciable probabilities (branching ratios ≈ 1).

When the above criteria are met, the expression above gives the exact analytical steady‑state concentration of \(^{233}\mathrm{U}\) in the closed‑cycle molten‑salt reactor as a function of the initial \(^{241}\mathrm{Am}\) loading and the listed nuclear‑physics parameters.

**Steady‑state population difference**

For a driven two‑level molecule (Rabi frequency \(\Omega\propto\sqrt I\), detuning \(\Delta=\omega_{0}-\omega_{L}\)) coupled weakly to the structured bath, the second‑order time‑convolutionless (TCL) master equation yields an effective longitudinal decay rate  

\[
\Gamma_{\mathrm{eff}}
 =\Gamma_{0}\Bigl[1+\alpha\cos(\beta\omega_{0})\Bigr]
 -\kappa\,\alpha\beta^{2}g^{2},
\qquad 
\Gamma_{0}=2\pi g^{2}\frac{\omega_{0}^{2}}{\pi^{2}c^{3}},
\]

where \(\kappa>0\) is a numerical constant (\(\kappa=2/15\) for a vacuum bath) and \(g\) is the molecule‑field coupling.  
The steady‑state Bloch‑vector solution gives  

\[
\boxed{\;
\Delta N\equiv\langle\sigma_{z}\rangle_{\rm ss}
   =-\frac{\Gamma_{\mathrm{eff}}^{2}+4\Delta^{2}}
          {\Gamma_{\mathrm{eff}}^{2}+4\Delta^{2}+2\Omega^{2}}
\;}
\tag{1}
\]

which reduces to the usual Lorentzian result when \(\alpha\!\to\!0\) (Markovian limit).

---

**Symmetry‑breaking phase transition**

Equation (1) is symmetric under \(\Delta\!\to\!-\Delta\) only for \(\alpha=0\).  
For \(\alpha\neq0\) the denominator can become stationary with respect to \(\Delta\) when  

\[
\frac{\partial\Delta N}{\partial\Delta}=0
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\Omega^{2}= \Gamma_{\mathrm{eff}}^{2}+4\Delta^{2}.
\tag{2}
\]

Using \(\Omega^{2}=c_{R}I\) (\(c_{R}\) a constant set by the dipole moment) the **critical laser intensity** at which the steady‑state solution bifurcates is  

\[
\boxed{\;
I_{c}= \frac{1}{c_{R}}
        \Bigl[\Gamma_{0}\bigl(1+\alpha\cos(\beta\omega_{0})\bigr)
              -\kappa\alpha\beta^{2}g^{2}\Bigr]^{2}
\;}
\tag{3}
\]

For \(I>I_{c}\) two distinct branches of \(\Delta N(\omega_{L})\) appear (one with larger excited‑state population, one with smaller), signalling spontaneous breaking of the \(\Delta\!\to\!-\Delta\) symmetry. The transition disappears when \(\alpha=0\), i.e. in the Markovian case.

---

**Non‑analyticity in photon‑count statistics**

Introducing a counting field \(\lambda\) into the TCL Liouvillian,
\[
\mathcal{L}_{\lambda}= \mathcal{L}_{0}
   +\bigl(e^{i\lambda}-1\bigr)\mathcal{J},
\qquad 
\mathcal{J}\rho =\Gamma_{\downarrow}\,\sigma_{-}\rho\sigma_{+},
\]
the cumulant‑generating function \(\chi(\lambda)\) is the dominant eigenvalue of \(\mathcal{L}_{\lambda}\).  
Close to the bifurcation the Liouvillian gap scales as  

\[
\Delta_{\rm gap}\sim |I-I_{c}|^{\nu},\qquad \nu=\tfrac12,
\]

which follows from a Wilsonian RG treatment of the marginal coupling \(\alpha\) (beta‑function \(d\alpha/d\ell=-\alpha^{2}\beta^{2}g^{2}/2\pi\)).  
Because the \(n\)‑th cumulant involves \(n\) derivatives of \(\chi(\lambda)\), the third cumulant diverges as  

\[
\boxed{\;
\kappa_{3}= \left.\frac{\partial^{3}\chi}{\partial(i\lambda)^{3}}\right|_{\lambda=0}
   \;\propto\; |I-I_{c}|^{-\gamma},
\qquad \gamma=3\nu=\frac{3}{2}
\;}
\tag{4}
\]

Thus the symmetry‑breaking point (3) manifests as a non‑analytic kink in the photon‑emission statistics, with the leading scaling \(\kappa_{3}\sim|I-I_{c}|^{-3/2}\).

